<HEADLINE> Palestinian Police Detain Suspected Murderer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Police have
detained a Hamas activist, who was suspected of murdering the
organization's bombmaker Muhi Sharif last month, Israel Radio
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It said that Adel Awadallah, leader of Hamas military wing
Izzadin Al-Qasam, is being held in the West Bank city of
Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Awadallah was detained amid continued exchange of accusation
between the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and the radical
militant group Hamas regarding Sharif's death.
</P>
<P>
The PNA announced Monday that Sharif was killed by six fellow
Hamas activists in an internal power struggle on March 29.
</P>
<P>
Five of them were arrested by the Palestinian security
forces early this month. But Awadallah, who was accused of
shooting Sharif to death, had been at large.
</P>
<P>
Hamas rejected the findings of the PNA's investigation, noting
that Israel should be responsible for the murder. In a videotape
released on Wednesday, a masked man, who claimed to be Awadallah,
further accused the PNA of collaborating with Israel in Sharif's
killing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, senior members of Islamic Jihad group in Gaza
said on Saturday that the Palestinian police have detained one
of their group's leaders Abdallah Ashami.
</P>
<P>
They said Ashami was arrested Thursday after claiming during
a summon in a Gaza Mosque that the PNA was behind the
death of Sharif.
</P>
<P>
In the last three days, the Palestinian police have also
reportedly detained three high-ranking Hamas members, including
the group's leader in Gaza Aziz Abdel Rantisi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
