<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-11 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Germany Continue Training Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of Education
Hussein Kamel Bahaa Eddin said Saturday that the German government
has agreed to extend the Mubarak-Kohl Project for technical
education up to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency quoted the minister as saying that
the decision was taken in the light of achievements realized since
the project was launched in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The joint Egyptian-German project, which was named after
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, aims to turn out for skilled workers to serve Egyptian
industry.
</P>
<P>
The project is being applied in 10 new Egyptian industrial
cities. More than 2,200 trainees are receiving instruction at 12
schools of the project.
</P>
<P>
Trainees receive on-the-job instruction in mechanics,
electronics, ready-to-wear clothes industries, heavy equipment,
nursing, weaving and leather crafts.
</P>
<P>
They are trained at factories which adopt the project and at
schools which are situated at the sites of the factories. More
than 62 German experts participated in the project.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-German ties have been going strong despite the
September 18 terrorist bombing last year in front of the Egyptian
Museum here, which killed nine German tourists and their Egyptian
driver.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the No. 1 tourist source for Egypt. Around 460,000
Germans come to visit Egypt annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
