<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pakistan Faces Daunting Task of Anti- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Increasingly rampant smuggling
has caused serious concern in Pakistan as this south Asian nation
is suffering losses estimated at hundreds of millions of U.S.
dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government, which is facing an acute shortfall of
revenue during the current fiscal year (July 1-June 30), has
adopted a series of measures to deal with the worsening situation.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures released by the Central Board of Revenue
(CBR) showed that during the first nine months of 1997-98, the
government has collected only 197 billion rupees (4.5 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
That has resulted an estimated shortfall of 30 billion rupees
(682 million dollars) in the revised down revenue target of 305
billion rupees (6.9 billion dollars) for the whole of 1997-98 and
the government is now hard-pressed to achieve the budget deficit
target of five percent of gross domestic product (GDP) set with
the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Smuggling along Pakistan's borders with neighboring countries
is one of the major causes for huge revenue losses by the central
government, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Smuggling has also badly hit the already stagnant industries
and much-needed foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
As a local press report said, the smuggling problem has led to
"a fearful state of stagnation never ever witnessed in the country
before."
</P>
<P>
Official sources confirmed that a high-level meeting was held
recently at the CBR to discuss a new drive to counter smuggling
and prepare a list of active smugglers.
</P>
<P>
The government, knowing that transit trade along the
Pakistani-Afghan border has been very brisk for a long time, has
taken a number of measures to stop the inflow of foreign goods
into Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Ishaq Dar has reportedly taken the charge of
an anti-smuggling operation, and the government is sealing off the
border with Afghanistan to curb smuggling activities with a view
to eliminating the so-called "parallel economy" involving billions
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
Former president of Balochistan Chamber of Commerce and
Industry Khalifa Tahir has proposed that Afghanistan should have
its own tariff structure.
</P>
<P>
He says that for Afghanistan, Pakistan's move to levy customs
tariff on transit goods would minimize the menace of smuggling and
be beneficial to inter-state trade.
</P>
<P>
Local economists say Tahir's proposal is practical and
feasible. The interests of local industries would be well
protected and Afghanistan would also benefit in monetary terms.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. report, smugglers have already established
a "parallel economy" in Pakistan, and the CBR is therefore
considering imposing customs duties on the Afghan transit trade.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Pakistan's loss of revenue from Customs is
around 30 billion rupees annually (682 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is also suffering huge revenue losses from unofficial
trade with its long-time rival neighbor of India.
</P>
<P>
Due to restrictive trade policies governing trade between the
two South Asian nations, a substantial amount of bilateral trade
originates as "parallel trade" in the form of unrecorded trade.
</P>
<P>
This includes smuggling through border trade and indirect trade
where Pakistani importers procure Indian goods via third places
like Dubai, Hong Kong and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial trade between Pakistan and India is estimated to be
two or four times the regular and official trade.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's free trade with India is restricted so as to protect
local industries from tough competition by Indian goods. Many
Pakistani business people are also opposing the move to give India
the Most-Favored Nation status, arguing that such a policy will
badly hit the domestic industry.
</P>
<P>
However, many other business people are in favor of opening
trade with India, saying Pakistan could benefit from the transfer
of Indian technology, especially in the field of engineering and
computer.
</P>
<P>
They also say Pakistan would be saving a large amount of
foreign exchange and that prices would come down since Indian
finished goods are much cheaper than similar goods being imported
from other countries and regions in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say direct trade with India would generate more
revenue for the government in the form of customs duties and It is
the most practical way of curbing illegal trade between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, direct trade is hardly possible at least in the near
future, as a number of outstanding problems between the two
arch-rivals in South Asia, including the Kashmir issue, are posing
a stumbling block to it.
</P>
<P>
And it seems a protracted process and a tough job for the
Pakistani government to stop the Afghan transit trade, or
smuggling, due to the on-going armed conflict in that war-ravaged
country, as well as political and economic reasons, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
