<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Democratic Congo Sign General Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Ethiopia
and Democratic Republic of Congo signed here on Saturday a
general agreement which will serve as a basis for the framework
of cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint communique issued here at the end of the
five-day state visit to Ethiopia by Democratic Congolese
president Laurent Desire Kabila, the agreement was signed by
president Kabila and Ethiopian president Negasso Gidada at a
ceremony held at the National Palace here.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the two presidents declared their determi-
nation to enhance and further strengthen the existing bonds of
friendship between the brotherly peoples of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It further said the two heads of state underlined the
importance of launching close cooperation in the political,
economic and social sectors.
</P>
<P>
The communique said, a joint ministerial meeting of the two
countries which was held here looked exhaustively into a number
of areas including agriculture, transport, small and medium-scale
enterprises, mining, energy, education and culture with a view to
deepening the expanding relations and bilateral cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the effective implementation of the general
agreement and to identify other possible areas of cooperation,
the two parties had agreed to establish a joint commission, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
On the regional issues, the communique said, the two leaders
agreed on the need to udnertake close consultation and
coordination of their positions with a view to consolidating
peace, stability and socio-economic development in the Horn of
Africa, the Great Lakes Region and Africa as a whole.
</P>
<P>
After exchanging views on the prevailing situation in the
Democratic Republic of Congo, the two leaders stressed the urgent
need for assistance by the international community in the
reconstruction and rehabilitation of the infrastructure in the
Democratic Congo.
</P>
<P>
President Kabila left here Saturday afternoon for Kinshasa
after concluding his five-day state visit to Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
He was seen off at the airport by president Negasso and senior
government officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
