<HEADLINE> Angolan Govt Urged For Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- An United Nations official said
here Saturday that the Angolan government should take effective
actions to guarantee stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
UN special envoy to Angola Blondin Beye said in central
Angola's Lobito city, where he was on his three-day visit, that
the situation in central Angola's Benguela Province, the Huila
Province in the south and Malanhe in the north is far from stable
and security is not yet guaranteed in the regions.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government should act in accordance with the
spirit of peace as outlined by the joint commission of peace
process in the country.
</P>
<P>
In another development, two cars of the Catholic missions are
attacked by military men of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), injuring two persons Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth time general citizens were attacked by the
UNITA military men in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Though non-militarization had been reached early last month,
some of the former UNITA military forces were still carrying on
military activities against the peace process in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
