<HEADLINE> Roundup: Interest Rate Battle Among Thai Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A slogan hung outside a Bangkok
branch of Laem Thong Bank looks very attractive. It says the bank
provides its customers with duty-free deposit accounts plus a
three percent special bonus.
</P>
<P>
This is the bank's new measure to attract deposits. In fact, a
battle for attracting deposits by raising interest rates has
already started among the 15 commercial banks in Thailand, which,
under the central bank's requirement, need to increase their
capital substantially.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Metropolitan Bank, Siam City Bank, First Bangkok City
Bank and Bangkok Bank of Commerce, the four banks taken over by
the government regulators after the financial crisis last July,
are offering an average deposit interest rate of as high as 16.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Raising deposits is necessary for the four banks to mobilize
funds to repay their outstanding loans to the financial
institutions development fund.
</P>
<P>
Due to the interest rates battle, deposits throughout the
banking system have shifted away from large commercial banks in
the first quarter of this year to small and medium-sized banks
such as Laem Thong Bank, which offer almost 400 basis points
higher interest than large banks.
</P>
<P>
According to figures of the Thai Bankers' association, the
hardest hit was Bangkok Bank, the country's largest bank, which
lost 28.36 billion baht (709 million U.S. dollars) in deposits
from January to February. It was followed by Siam Commercial Bank
with a drop of 20.26 billion baht (506.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
To meet the challenges, big banks took their actions. Bangkok
Bank branch managers were instructed to use their own judgment in
offering deposit interest rates to favored customers.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank currently offers fixed deposit rates of 10-12.75
percent, but managers are now authorized to offer up to 300 basis
points more to maintain their deposit base, one executive said.
</P>
<P>
Higher deposit rates lead to the soaring cost of the banking
operations. Banks were forced to increase their lending interest
rates to make profit.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Bangkok Bank increased its lending interest
rates by 25-75 basis points, setting its minimum lending rate at
15.5 percent. Other banks are expected to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's banks, faced with the need to increase loan-loss
provisions, have exploited high rates by mobilizing deposits for
relending in the money market, which offers higher spreads and
lower risks than lending to retail or corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
The fierce competition for funds is exacting its own toll on
the overall economy by preventing lending rates from easing,
squeezing the corporate sector.
</P>
<P>
Many cash-strapped businesses in the country complain that the
banks' reluctance to extend new credit was squeezing cashflow and
delaying prospects of an economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said recently that
interest rate rises reflected continued tight liquidity in the
financial system, which in turn requires the central bank to keep
its policy of high interest rates unchanged to lure more funds
into the country.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said interest rate declines were impossible until the
basic problems of the economy were tackled and liquidity pressure
eased.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has also underlined the
importance of maintaining high interest rates to attract capital
inflow.
</P>
<P>
He said that once there was sufficient capital, the liquidity
problem would be eased and interest rates go down automatically.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he conceded that, in the long run, high interest
rates would be damaging to the economy and would drive many
businesses to go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
There is no sign yet of a "cease-fire" in Thai banks' battle of
interest rates. Businesses have to suffer more, and people are
told that it's the price the country has to pay for the financial
crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
