<HEADLINE> Pakistan Pledges to Do Away With Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Labor Minister Sheikh Rashid
Ahmed said on Saturday that Pakistan would fully abide by the
international obligations for eliminating child labor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the eve of the global march against
Child Labor, Sheikh stressed the need for world-wide steps towards
economic revival and poverty alleviation to stamp out child labor.
</P>
<P>
Child labor is a complex issue, and a high degree of
determination is needed to combat it, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government is fully committed to the elimination of child
labor, he said.
</P>
<P>
Three to four schools had been set up in each constituency of
the National Assembly for children engaged in labor and more than
60 rehabilitation centers had been established across the country,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has also set up four task forces to
tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the participants of the global march, which will
enter Pakistan on April 13, he pledged the government's full
support for the 1,000 non-governmental organizations from more
than 80 countries which have organized the march.  
</P>
</TEXT>
