<HEADLINE> Paint Can Be Indication of Corroding Metal: Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A type of paint that changes
colors when the metal underneath corrodes is being developed by a
group of American researchers, New Scientist magazine reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The paint, tested at Ohio State University, the United States,
is still years away from commercial application, but it may
eventually be used to reveal early signs of corrosion on aircraft,
the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary studies in the lab have shown that the paint
changed colors around corrosion pits a thousandth of a centimetre
deep, which are too small to be seen with the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
The paint, a mixture of clear acrylic paint with Ph indicators
that react to the Ph changes associated with the corrosion
reactions, can change color with any increase in acidity or
alkalinity.
</P>
<P>
However, the method only works with clear paint and cannot be
used on parts of the plane covered with colored paints. Instead,
researchers are developing another kind of paint that fluoresces
in ultraviolet light when the Ph changes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
