<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Launch Economic Growth Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Government has
announced a three-year economic program aiming at economic
growth and poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
Prosper Musafari, Director of Macro-Economic Policy in the
Ministry of Planning, said that this program will start in August
1998 and end in the year 2001, according to Rwanda News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The program targets at a 7.5 percent economic growth, while
keeping the inflation rate down at 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government will also need to carry out fiscal,
monetary, and structural policy reforms that would keep inflation
down, and safeguard stable exchange rate of the Rwandan Franc.
</P>
<P>
Musafari said structural and institutional reforms envisaged
by the government will focus on the promotion of the private
sector by encouraging both domestic and foreign private
investment, the reform of the civil service which implies the
retrenchment of some workers, and turning the agriculture-based
Rwandan economy into an export-oriented one.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan Ministry of Finance and Planning, however, has
indicated that this program will largely depend on foreign aid,
with regard to a 200 million US Dollars gap that needs to be
bridged up.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral and multilateral creditors who have come up with
promises to help narrow down this financial gap, include the
World Bank with 60 million dollars for the year to come, the
European Union 42 million, the African Development Bank 20
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund promised 72 million U.S.
Dollars in support of the balance of payment, and Holland about
22 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
In order to successfully implement the program, some reforms
going in line with better management of public resources, the
support of the private sector, and the strengthening of the
existing infrastructures, as well as the creation of others, will
be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Other measures will have to do with enhancing good governance
and accountability, and promoting investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
