<HEADLINE> Kurdish Rebels Attack Military Helicopter in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) has attacked a military helicopter in the
southeastern province of Sirnak, killing a village guard, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened late Friday night when PKK militants
raided the helicopter carrying security forces to the region to
reinforce fightings against the rebels, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter sustained minor damages in the attack, but
landed safely, it added.
</P>
<P>
Emergency Regional Rule Governor Aydin Arslan was quoted by the
news agency as saying that 25,000 PKK rebels were rendered
ineffective since Turkey imposed the state of emergency in the
southeast in a bid to wipe out PKK militants in 1987.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 14-year-old war for autonomy in
eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The PKK militants, who have sought shelters in northern Iraq
since 1991, often launch cross-border attacks on Turkey's military
and civilian targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
