<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Marks Bicentenary of Birth of Delacroix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- France is marking the bicentenary
of the birth of one of the greatest painters in the world in 19th
century, Eugene Delacroix, the author of "Liberty Guides the
People," "The Death of Sardanapale," and "the Massacres of Scio."
</P>
<P>
Several exhibitions are being held in Paris and a number of
other French cities to memorize the great painter who was a
milestone of both neo-classicism and romanticism.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition of the latter-day works of Delacroix is being
held in the Grand Palace in Paris, displaying all the paintings
done by him from 1850 to 1863, the year when he died.
</P>
<P>
Born in a great Bourgeois mansion in Charenton-Saint-Maurice
near Paris on April 26, 1798, Delacroix was also the master
painter of decorations in the great Paris palaces such as the
Bourbon Palace where the French National Assembly is based, the
Luxembourg Palace where is the French Senate, and the City Hall of
Paris.
</P>
<P>
Included in the exhibition in the Grand Palace are the famous
"Lion Hunt" series, depiction of violent fight between a hunter
and a lion which he saw when he made a tour to North Africa in
1832.
</P>
<P>
His paintings of pasturage and flowers, which were strongly
influenced by his contemporary British water-colorists and by his
precedding compatriots Le Lorrain and Nicolas Poussin in the 17th
century, were also displayed in the Grand Palace.
</P>
<P>
The house in Saint-Maurice in which Delacroix was born will
also open to the public from April 25 to June 28, and exhibitions
of his works are also being displayed in Rouen, Tour, Chantilly
and the Louvre Museum in Paris.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
