<HEADLINE> Iraqi Parliament Slams British Proposal for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 11 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) Saturday called for issuing a statement unveiling the
"ill intentions" behind a British proposal for hosting a
conference on the Iraqi-U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Britain has called for a meeting in London of the program's
various bodies and aid organizations to work out ways of speeding
up the delivery of humanitarian goods under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
During its first spring session Saturday, the assembly decided
to send a delegation to the Damascus-based Arab
Inter-Parliamentary Union in order to abort the proposed
conference, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It said that the statement will be addressed to national,
regional and international parliamentary unions.
</P>
<P>
The assembly also stressed the need to send a telegram to
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, urging him to allow no party
other than the United Nations to discuss any matter concerning
Iraq-related U.N. resolutions without the consent of the Iraqi
government.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the assembly's Arab and International Relations
Committee Saad Qassim Hammoudi said that the aims behind the
British proposal unmasked part of the wicked and hypocritical
approach long pursued by the British government against the people
of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the British proposal is dubious in timing and in
content, accusing Britain of collaborating with the United States
to prolong the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"Britain is trying to take advantage of its current presidency
of the European Union to rally support for the British-American
scheme," said Hammoudi. "The proposal is of political purpose,
not humanitarian one," he told reporters outside the building of
the assembly.
</P>
<P>
Hammoudi said Iraq had dealt positively with every proposal
aimed at ensuring swift implementation of the oil-for-food deal,
whether in relations to the financial allocations or to the
improvement of the mechanism of implementation in a way to
achieve its humanitarian target as a temporary measure, rather
than an alternative to the lifting of the U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the British representative in the U.N. Sanctions
Committee on Iraq had always sought to block or put on hold the
food and medicine contracts Iraq had concluded under the
memorandum of understanding reached with the United Nations on
May 20, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is allowed to sell up to 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil over six months, from the present 2 billion dollars, to buy
food and medicines for its people suffering from the crippling
sanctions imposed after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
