<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A total of 5,584 Iraqi prisoners
of war released by Iran have come back home, Iraqi Foreign
Under-Secretary Riyadh al-Qaisi said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview, al-Qaisi said that in a new round
of repatriation of POWs early this month, Iran freed 5,592 Iraqis,
of whom one died of heart attack during the process and seven
others refused to return home.
</P>
<P>
During the biggest POW swap between the two countries since
1990, Iraq also freed three Iranian POWs and 316 others it
classified as civil law detainees.
</P>
<P>
The POWs were captured during the 1980-88 Iraq-Iran war.
</P>
<P>
The move came as a result of recent talks between the two
former foes in an effort to warm up their relations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Qaisi said that another round of talks on the issue will be
held between the two sides on April 18 in Baghdad and it will last
for about a week.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue our talks with Iranian officials to get
information on Iraqi soldiers held by Iran," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq will also ask the Red Crescent to interview those who
have refused to return," the Iraqi official said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will also be concerned about those missing in the war, he
added. 
</P>
