<HEADLINE> Egypt to Set up New Industrial Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri Saturday announced a decision to set up a new
industrial zone in Upper Egypt, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the General Investments Authority and Free Zones
Ibrahim Fawzi said projects to be set up on an area of 2,000
feddans (84 hectares) in Fayoum governorate, about 120 kilometers
south of Cairo, will benefit from privileges, exemptions and
guarantees provided under the investment incentives and guarantees
law.
</P>
<P>
Projects to be set up in this zone will be exempted from taxes
for 10 years and will enjoy other facilities such as being
provided with land complete with the infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the new industrial zone in Fayoum is part
of the government's plan to develop Upper Egyptian governorates
and contribute to providing job opportunities, activating exports
and maximizing national product.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is trying to narrow the gap between Lower Delta areas and
Upper Egyptian governorates that suffer from a chronic lack of
investment and are denied an equal share of attention.
</P>
<P>
In the past 30 years, Egypt has built altogether 26 industrial
zones where products manufactured according to local conditions
are mostly for export. 
</P>
