<HEADLINE> Egypt: U.S., EU Still Involved in Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt expressed its conviction
Saturday that the United States and European Union can not walk
away from the Mideast peace process, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"I believe no major power, including the U.S. and the EU in
particular, can wash their hands off the peace process due to
grave prospects of failure or suspension of the peace process,"
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that peace in the Middle East is an integral part
of world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is still calling on the U.S. to openly announce its
initiative and the stances of the parties concerned on this
initiative, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are also calling for the U.S. role as an honest broker
seeking to reach a balanced peace among parties based on good
faith and commitment to the signed peace agreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's statement came before U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis
Ross is expected to return to the Mideast late in April in what is
viewed as his last bid to press the U.S. initiative via quiet
diplomacy to break the year-long deadlock in Mideast peace-making.
</P>
<P>
Washington reportedly wants Israel to pull back from 13.1
percent of the West Bank over 12 weeks accompanied by security
cooperation from the Palestinians. But it has not publically or
officially announced the initiative yet.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has warned that the
United States will wash its hands off the peace process if Israel
insisted on rejecting its offer.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming visit to the region by British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, which apparently overlaps with Ross' tour, is expected to
help press the Israeli government to accept the U.S. proposals.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled for months over
Israeli construction of a new settlement in Arab East Jerusalem
and long-delayed troop redeployment in the West bank. 
