<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Backs Palestinians to Fulfil Rights: Majali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Prime Minister Abdul-Salam
Majali said here Sunday that Jordan will always support the
Palestinians in their endeavor to fulfil their rights.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with heads of media departments at the
Information Ministry, Majali said the kingdom will especially
support the Palestinians in the pursuit of establishing their own
independent state with Jerusalem as the capital.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Majali said, Jordan stresses the importance
of resuming the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks which have been
stalled since March 1997 when Israel broke ground for construction
of a controversial Jewish neighborhood in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
By restarting the talks, it is expected to break the current
stalemate caused by the Israeli government hardline policy, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Majali called on the Israeli government to fulfill
its commitment to peace. "It is the only means to bring about
peace and stability to the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, Israel rejected a U.S. proposal calling for
Israeli troop redeployment from 13.1 percent of the West Bank over
12 weeks, arguing that any pullback more than 9 percent will
jeopardize its security.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli opposition rendered the mission of U.S. peace envoy
Dennis Ross to the Middle East region a failure. Jordan, which
signed peace with Israel in 1994, refrained from being critical of
Israel's hardline policies, but expressed satisfaction with the
Palestinians' coordination with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Ross is expected to be back in the region soon in a
"last-ditch" effort to persuade both sides to compromise over a
revised withdrawal plan, which reportedly demands Israel to turn
over 9 percent of the West Bank to full Palestinian control and
another 3 percent to Palestinian civil control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
