<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Enjoys Thriving Urban Cooperative Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 79 urban cooperative banks
have opened in Chinese cities, according to information presented
during a conference of bank directors which opened today in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the two-day conference will discuss effective
methods for ensuring the sound development of related banks,
avoiding financial risks and increasing competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources indicate that additional cities are preparing
to establish joint-stock commercial banking institutions.
</P>
<P>
China's first urban cooperative bank opened in 1995 in
Shenzhen, the nation's first special economic zone in Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the savings deposit balance for the Beijing Urban
Cooperative Bank closed at 34.5 billion yuan (4.15 billion US
dollars), with the loan balance standing at 15.06 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The end of last year's savings deposit balance for the Shanghai
Urban Cooperative Bank stood at 43.1 billion yuan, with the loan
balance ending at 23 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
