<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Libya have reached an agreement to set up a
joint technical committee to evaluate a big pipeline project,
according to the Lebanese Al Hayat daily.
</P>
<P>
The committee will undertake technical and economic feasibility
studies on the construction of a pipeline to transport Libyan
crude oil to Egypt with an amount of 150,000 barrels per day for
refining.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Botswana have set up a joint venture at a
cost of 90 million U.S. dollars to produce aluminium, the Al Hayat
daily said.
</P>
<P>
Michel Mulivani, chairman of Botswana's Development Authority,
said the output of the plant would satisfy local consumption and
the rest would be exported.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Tunisian export promotion center organized a
week-long fair from March 7 to 13 in Saudi capital Riyadh to
exhibit commodities including food, appliances, furniture, carpet
and artistic heritage.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A six-man delegation of Lebanese industrialists
started a visit to Iraq last week, seeking a share of the United
Nations oil-for-food program, under which Iraq can import
humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Industrialists Association President Jacques Sarraf
said that Lebanese private sector is looking for markets for its
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
