<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Congress Decides to Form One-Party Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali Congress (NC), the
largest party in parliament, decided Sunday to form a minority
government on its own strength, but there is a possibility that it
might try to find a ruling partner, an informed source said.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the NC and the Communist Party of Nepal
(Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML), the NC's chosen potential ruling
partner, on formation of a coalition government reached a deadlock
over allocation of portfolios, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-ML is a breakaway faction of the main opposition
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML).
</P>
<P>
The NC's decision to form a minority government amounts to a
suicidal game, a minister of the care-taker government was quoted
by the source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minority government led by Man Mohan Adhikari of the
CPN-UML about three years ago lasted only 10 months.
</P>
<P>
As the general elections are due by November 1999, the scramble
for power is sure to become more tense in the country, so the
possibility can not be ruled out that the NC will rethink its
decision and try to find a ruling partner to make a stable
government, the source said.
</P>
<P>
When accepting the resignation tendered last Friday by Prime
Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa, King Birendra asked members of the
lower house of parliament who can muster a simple majority of 103
votes in the 205-seat House to stake a claim to power by 18:00
p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Coalition politics emerged in Nepal after the mid-term polls in
November 1994 produced a hung parliament where no single party
commands a majority. The NC has only 87 MPs in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Under Nepal's constitution, in the event that a coalition
government cannot be formed, King Birendra may ask the party with
the largest number of MPs in the house to form a government.
</P>
<P>
Surya Bahadur Thapa stepped down to make way for the NC, one of
his ruling partners, to lead a new government under an agreement
he reached before he took office last October.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
