<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Minister Calls for Referendum over Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran's moderate Interior Minister
Abdullah Nouri Saturday called for a referendum to determine the
case of Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi who was detained for
alleged financial scandal.
</P>
<P>
The moderate newspaper Iran Daily Sunday quoted Nouri as
saying that a referendum must be held to show the people's stance
on Tehran mayor's case and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
"If the case of the (Tehran) mayor and the municipality is a
national issue, why is a poll not conducted to learn of the
people's views?" he asked in a speech at a meeting of mayors of
Tehran's 20 districts.
</P>
<P>
The minister termed Karbaschi's detention "outrageous,"
saying that the arrest of a person "who until yesterday would
attend cabinet meetings and make decisions in the interest of the
system and the (Islamic) revolution is totally unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Nouri, a major aide and supporter of President Mohammad
Khatami, also recalled the decrees of late Iranian supreme leader
Ayatollah Musavi Khomeini to defend Karbaschi for his dauntless
reforms in the capital city during the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
The late leader Imam Khomeini very rarely used the word
"intellectual" for a person, but in one of his decrees to
Karbaschi, he called the mayor "an intellectual of the
revolution," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also announced the formation of a special center
to defend Tehran mayor at the Interior Ministry premises by
gathering documents about Tehran municipality and Karbaschi's
achievements during the past years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, presidential advisor and secretary general of the
council of free trade zones Morteza Alviri called Karbaschi a
"national hero," saying that those who are fighting against the
mayor intend to revenge the construction period under the
leadership of former president Hashemi Rafsanjani and the
landslide victory of present President Mohammad Khatami in last
May's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the pro-Khatami newspaper Iran News, Alviri said
that it would be to the nation's benefit to free Karbaschi and
try those who have created the scenario because if the government
failed to try the culprits the people would rise and question
them.
</P>
<P>
The 44-year-old mayor was detained last week on an alleged
financial scandal. But his supporters were reportedly mobilizing
to rescue him from the attacks of the conservatives, calling on
supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei to arbitrate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
