<HEADLINE> Liaoning Governor Urges Assistance for Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Guoguang, governor of
northeast China's Liaoning Province, today urged the mayors of the
province's 14 major cities to help 400,000 laid-off workers find
new jobs within the year.
</P>
<P>
Local governments must shoulder the responsibility for ensuring
the reemployment of laid-off workers, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning, which leads all other provinces in terms of workers
in state-owned enterprises, has helped 1.22 million people,
including one million laid-off workers, find jobs over the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1997 listed 1.17 million unemployed
people. Officials estimate the province will have an additional
one million jobless people over the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has pledged to help 1.2 million
laid-off workers find new opportunities over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers are being encouraged to engage in agricultural
production in rural areas or to work in other parts of the
country. Some laid-off workers are also expected to find new
opportunities with businesses in the service sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
