<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In-depth Reforms Required to Fulfill Economic Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China will expand domestic demand
and accelerate economic restructuring in order to ensure
fulfillment of the eight percent economic growth rate targeted for
1998, said Zeng Peiyan, minister of the new State Development
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The government will boost demand by investing more in
agriculture, forestry, water conservation, railways and highways,
telecommunications, environmental protection, technological
upgrades and housing, said Zeng.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that related investments will not spark an
overheated economy, but integrate the expansion of domestic demand
with improvements in the industrial pattern.
</P>
<P>
In terms of macro-controls, the government will place priority
on carrying out reform of the financial system, grain circulation
and urban housing, said the minister, adding that his commission
will shoulder most of the burden.
</P>
<P>
The goal of reform is to further diminish the remnants of the
planned economy in related areas, according to Zeng.
</P>
<P>
The commission's major tasks in the future will focus on
formulating the nation's medium- and long-term development
programs, balancing overall supply and demand, improving the
industrial pattern, and strengthening controls over pricing,
investments and state material reserves, said Zeng. 
</P>
</TEXT>
