<HEADLINE> Iran Starts Joint Maneuvers in Persian Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Iranian armed forces Sunday
started a 10-day joint maneuvers in the Persian Gulf and Gulf of
Oman in order to strengthen its defensive capabilities, Tehran
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The war game with the code name of "Ettehad" (Unity) will be
held in three phases on the ground and under water in an area of
15,000 square nautical miles from Iran's southern port of Bandar
Abbas in the Persian Gulf to Chabahar in the Gulf of Oman.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, three Russian-made submarines will also
join the military exercises with two frigates, two personnel
carrier vessels, two logistic vessels and teams of frogmen along
with 15,000 personnel of naval and air forces.
</P>
<P>
Commander of Iran's naval forces Admiral Abbas Mohtaj said at a
press conference Saturday that the maneuver would be a blend of
operations of the three forces of army, navy and air forces.
</P>
<P>
He said the war game would prove that the Iranian naval forces
have acquired full knowledge and expertise to make optimum use of
its submarines bought from Russia since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
