<HEADLINE> Pakistan Refutes Allegations of Foreign Aid to Missile Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Sunday strongly
refuted the allegations of foreign aid to its development of a new
surface to surface missile.
</P>
<P>
"Such reports, emanating from abroad, are not only baseless but
also betray ulterior motives," a Foreign Office spokesman said in
a statement issued here.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to a report carried by the New York Times on
Saturday that the Hatf-V (Ghauri) missile test-fired by Pakistan
on April 6 was smuggled from the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
"Ghauri is indigenous in all aspects. It represents Pakistan's
own scientific and technological capabilities," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan desires peace and stability in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have no aggressive designs against anybody. Our aim is to
make Pakistan's defense impregnable," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted, "while augmenting our defense capability,
we shall continue to pursue dialogue and contribute meaningfully
to all efforts to remove the causes of tension and conflict in the
region." 
</P>
</TEXT>
