<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Wall Section Discovered in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered a new section of the ancient Great Wall, a structure
which dates back well over 2,000 years, in north China's Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region, according to China Youth Daily.
</P>
<P>
The section meanders for over 200 km through sparsely populated
areas near the Urad Front Banner of the region.
</P>
<P>
Ancient Chinese used locally quarried black stones to build the
wall which is 5-6 meter high and three meters wide, according to
archeologists.
</P>
<P>
The remoteness of the section has ensured that it remains
virtually intact.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists point to the discovery of the section as
equalling the significance of an earlier find by Professor Luo
Zhewen, a specialist in the history of the Great Wall. Luo
discovered a section of the wall dating to the Qin Dynasty
(1644-1911) near the city of Baotou in the same region.
</P>
<P>
The section features small beacon towers located one kilometer
apart, with large beacon towers found every five kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Experts point out the section, one of the most highly preserved
sections found in recent years, is a rare historical treasure
which will greatly enhance future research.
</P>
<P>
Historical documents attest to the fact that Qin Shihuang,
China's first emperor who began his reign 221 B.C., dispatched
troops led by General Meng Tian to build the wall in today's Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists working in the region have also unearthed a
cache of cultural relics dating to the Qin Dynasty, with said
objects clearly proving the age of the section.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities have listed section as a key protected
cultural relics site.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the State Bureau of Cultural Relics plans to
provide funds and technical assistance for the protection
effort, according to local officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0055 </DOCNO>
