<HEADLINE> Israeli Warplanes Raid South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes Sunday carried
out a series of air raids on suspected Lebanese guerrilla
positions in south Lebanon, Lebanese Orient Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Israeli fighters swooped down on a mountainous area between
the towns of Armetai and Sujud in the eastern sector of an
Israeli-occupied border enclave in south Lebanon on Sunday
morning, Lebanese security sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The area is believed to be used by the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah guerrillas as a base for operations against Israeli
soldiers and their militia allies South Lebanese Army (SLA).
</P>
<P>
A Hezbollah spokesman said in a statement that Israeli planes
attacked al-Iqlim Toufaha area and dropped a total of eight
air-to-surface missiles.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army sources also confirmed the air raids, but
stressed that they attacked Hezbollah's military bases, not
villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
There has been no report of casualties caused by the air raids.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, leads a guerrilla war to oust
Israel's 2,000 soldiers and the 2,500 SLA militiamen from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer self-styled security
zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with the aim of protecting its
northern villages and towns from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
