<HEADLINE> Aussies Sweeps 1-2-3 Spots in  World Cup Triathlon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- World champion Emma Carney led an
Australian sweep of the top three positions in women's event and
made it an Australian double with Greg Welch in the opener of the
World Cup triathlon in Ishigakijima on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Triathlon will make its Olympic debut in the 2000 Games with
Carney as the top favourite in Sydney. She clocked two hours three
minutes 24 seconds over three categories beating fellow
Australians Jackie Gallagher and Michellie Jones.
</P>
<P>
Carney was only 26th in the first 1.5-kilometre swimming
section in 19:41, but she clocked the fastest times in the 40km
bike and 10km running sections with 1:07:01 and 36:42.
</P>
<P>
Carney, the winner of six World Cup races last season to finish
atop in the rankings, was almost two minutes faster than Gallagher
in 2:05:05 and Jones in 2:05:48, while Isabelle Mouthon of France
came in fourth in 2:05:59.
</P>
<P>
In the men's event, Welch held on to a three-second victory in
a close battle against Jamie Hunt of New Zealand at the final
stage crossing the line in 1:50:57.
</P>
<P>
His compatriots Chris Hill was third in 1:51:13 and Greg
Bennett fourth in 1:51:23, while the men's world champion and
defending champion Chris McCormack, also from Australia, finished
at a lowly 10th in 1:52:52. 
</P>
