<HEADLINE> Outlawed S. African Pesticides to Be Disposed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is to ship
hundreds of tons of internationally outlawed and obsolete
pesticides to Britain for disposal, the Sunday Independent
reported.
</P>
<P>
Among the poisons to be shipped out are stocks of
controversial DDT and dieldrin, which have been in use in South
Africa even though they are banned in most countries.
</P>
<P>
The cleanup operation involves between 750 and 800 tons of
potentially deadly pesticides originally intended for
agricultural use, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The poison will be moved to Wales, Britain, where Rechem, a
disposal company will incinerate it.
</P>
<P>
Etienne Wolmarans, the Agriculture Department's registrar for
pesticide, was quoted as saying that Rechem won the tender
because it had a good record on pesticide disposal in Europe and
there was no such facility in the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
This is a reversal of the usual trend of developed countries
sending toxic waste to the undeveloped countries for disposal.
</P>
<P>
Jan Kleynhans, Director of the Crop Protection and Animal
Health Association, said the chemicals had to be removed as they
posed an extreme danger to people and the environment.
</P>
<P>
He said that many drums of pesticide bought for farming over
the past 40 years had never been used and lay discarded on farms.
However, the director added that the lion's share of South
Africa's obsolete pesticide stock lay in government depots.
</P>
<P>
Kleynhans said that his association, which was co-ordinating
the retrieval process for the government, had also offered its
services to Namibia and Swaziland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Campaign War Intensifying in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- With the May 11 presidential
elections just one month away, presidential candidates in the
Philippines have stepped up not only electioneering all over the
country but also backstage political maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
At this point in the campaign, analysts say, mudslinging
between rival candidates may intensify and a new round of
political realignments among the 11 official presidential
candidates could emerge.
</P>
<P>
And some candidates without sufficient fund and strong
political machinery will likely bow out of the race.
</P>
<P>
Various surveys conducted recently by different polling groups
indicated a three-cornered fight in the coming polls among Vice
President Joseph Estrada of the United Opposition, Manila Mayor
Alfredo Lim of the Liberal Party and Speaker of the House of
Representatives Jose de Venecia of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, a former action movie star popular among the ordinary
masses, has led in all the three public opinion polls conducted
since January this year by the Social Weather Stations (SWS), a
leading independent pollster in the country.
</P>
<P>
The 60-year-old Estrada, nicknamed "Erap", has been a clear
favorite for the respondents with a 28 percent supporting rate in
the latest SWS poll despite repeated mudslinging by his rivals
during recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
In the same poll, De Venecia, who has ranked poorly in previous
SWS surveys, jumped to second place with 14 percent in a tie with
Alfredo Lim, who has the backing of former president Corazon
Aquino and, allegedly, the country's powerful Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
It seems that De Venecia, who enjoys the strong support of
President Fidel Ramos, still has a slim chance to catch up with
Estrada, on whom De Venecia's camp has reportedly undertaken a
"demolition job" since last month.
</P>
<P>
Among the charges against Estrada were his involvement in a
financial scandal and his secret plan to assassinate Ramos in
order to obtain the country's highest post at an early date.
</P>
<P>
Both charges were bluntly denied by Estrada whose camp
counter-charged that Ramos and other administration officials were
involved in a land scandal.
</P>
<P>
Alfredo Lim, a Filipino-Chinese, was also under attack. His
rivals instigated a lawyer to ask the Commission on Elections
(Comelec) to question Lim's citizenship.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer said in a petition that Lim is not a natural-born
Filipino because his parents were Chinese "mestizos." Under the
constitution, only natural-born Filipinos may seek the presidency.
The Comelec will rule on this petition soon.
</P>
<P>
There are still no signs yet that such muckraking may subside.
Instead, many fear that mudslinging and black propaganda will
intensify as the election day is fast approaching.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, political regroupings among different political
forces are expected during the remaining 30 campaign days as some
candidates are running out of their funds.
</P>
<P>
Lack of political strength may also force some lower-ranking
candidates to give up and shift their backing to those
front-runners who have better chances to win in the national
polls.
</P>
<P>
Among the 11 presidential contenders, only the ruling party and
Estrada's United Opposition have nationwide grassroots
organizations and put up a complete senatorial slate for the May
polls.
</P>
<P>
During the May polls, voters will also elect 12 of the
24-member Senate. A complete senatorial ticket is seen as a vital
gauge of a party's political strength since senators are elected
by national votes.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, regrouping will also take place among the
generous financiers of certain presidential candidates who remain
at the tail end of the popularity polls.
</P>
<P>
The financiers of those who have not figured prominently in the
presidential race will start looking for other candidates with
better chances to win in the general elections, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
