<HEADLINE> Nigerian Parties to Decide on Abacha's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's five political parties
are expected to decide at their national conventions this week on
the controversial issue of adopting Sani Abacha as their
consensus presidential candidate, media reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The parties reportedly received an instruction from the
government earlier this month, urging them to hold their national
conventions not later than this week.
</P>
<P>
The parties declined the order at first, as the national
assembly election is near on April 25, but reports said they might
have given in to pressure now.
</P>
<P>
The National Center Party of Nigeria has announced that it
will hold its national convention Saturday in Owerri, on which a
presidential candidate will be adopted.
</P>
<P>
The United Nigeria Congress Party, which saw landslide
victories in elections under the transition to civil rule program
so far, will hold its national convention Thursday in Kaduna, the
Sunday Punch newspaper said. But another newspaper, the Sunday
Tribune, said the convention is scheduled to be held on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The other parties, the Democratic Party of Nigeria, the
Congress for National Consensus and the Grassroot Democratic
Movement (GDM) will all have their national conventions Saturday,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Less than four months left from the August 1 presidential elections,
all the five parties have not announced their candidates, hence
strengthening the wide suspicion that they have a hidden agenda
of adopting General Abacha as their consensus candidate.
</P>
<P>
Two politicians, Alhaji Momammed Yusufu and Tunji Braithwaite,
have expressed their wish to run on the platform of the GDM, but
the party has not decided whom it will accept. 
</P>
