<HEADLINE> Public Servants Urged to Telling Truth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Outlook, China's leading weekly
news magazine, will include an editorial tomorrow, hailing the
establishment of a favorable environment to encourage people to
tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
The editorial stresses that Premier Zhu Rongji's call for every
member of the State Council to assiduously practice truthfulness
could be adopted as a requirement for the country's gigantic work
force of public servants.
</P>
<P>
Full and genuine implementation of the goal will be an arduous
task, which will be highly to both the State and the people when
accomplished, according to the editorial.
</P>
<P>
The editorial also stresses that those caught telling lies
should be punished in full accordance with the law and with total
disregard for social status.
</P>
<P>
The editorial stresses that those failing to adhere to the
principle of seeking truth from facts, the ideological line of the
Communist Party of China, are unqualified to work as public
servants or enjoy membership in the CPC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
