<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Top-Dying Disease" Spreading in World's Largest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- "Top-Dying Disease" is spreading
fast in Bangladesh's Sundarbans, the largest mangrove forest in
the world, The Bangladesh Observer newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sundari tree, the main variety of the trees in the forest, has
been seriously attacked by the killer disease which eats up the
tree from the top downwards.
</P>
<P>
The Sundarbans mangrove forest is located near Khulna district,
about 320 km southwest of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Forty percent of the 5,800-square-km forest fringing the Bay of
Bengal is already affected by the "top-dying disease," according
to other press reports.
</P>
<P>
If a way to stop the disease from spreading is not found, the
Sundari tree may be extinct in the near future, the newspaper
said, quoting botanists.
</P>
<P>
But the causes of the disease are yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to stop the disease, scientists have begun a
three-year project funded by the British government's Overseas
Development Administration to monitor the forest.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program also conducted four
years of research on the Sundarbans but failed to detect the
causes of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Increased salinity in the local rivers caused by withdrawal of
Ganges water of Farakka Barrage might by one reason for spreading
the disease, the Bangladesh Development Research Center said.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Water Development Board (BWDB) also mentioned
high salinity as the cause of the destruction of Sundari trees.
</P>
<P>
Salinity of rivers like Jamuna, Ichhamoti, Kobadak, Kholpetua,
Raimongol, Malancha and Mongla flowing by the Sundarbans was up to
10 times the normal level, according to the BWDB.
</P>
<P>
That abnormally high level of salinity is causing not only the
top-dying disease but also destroying the seeds on the ground,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Sundari trees are used to growing mainly in the areas
washed by the tide, and now saline water remains stagnant for a
long time, preventing the growth of the plants, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
It is fungal disease which has caused the top-dying disease to
spread, according to Prof. M. Abdur Rahman of Forestry and Wood
Technology Department of the Khulna University. However, the type
of fungus could not be determined now, he said.
</P>
<P>
The affected trees should be cut down to protect the healthy
ones in the area, some forest officials suggested.
</P>
<P>
Foreign experts have also been contacted and technological
assistance sought to find out the causes of the disease and save
the Sundarbans from extinction, the newspaper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
