<HEADLINE> 3,000 Zambian Copper Miners to Lose Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- At least 3,000 employees from
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) are ear-marked for
retrenchment as the state-owned mining conglomerate privatizes
its divisions, Sunday Times of Zambia reported.
</P>
<P>
In the same exercise, the mining company will not renew the
contracts for expatriate workers as well as selected jobs held by
Zambians, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Paul Kafumbe, President of Mineworkers Union of
Zambia (MUZ), as saying in an interview Saturday that he was
aware that 3,000 miners will be retrenched, but his union is
negotiating with ZCCM to keep the numbers low, preferably 1,000
workers.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the decision by ZCCM not to renew contracts of
expatriate workers as Zambia has a lot of well-qualified
engineers to adequately man the mines.
</P>
<P>
With several divisions privatized, ZCCM labor force stands at
an estimated 38,000 employees from the previous 65,000 before the
privatization of the country's biggest foreign exchange earner
which started two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Though not stating the exact number of employees to be laid
off, ZCCM senior official Sam Equamo told the paper Saturday that
the company is currently reducing the number of employees at the
head office and the operations center since the two units will
have little or no role to play when other units are privatized.
</P>
<P>
Most contracts for expatriates and Zambians will not be
renewed in the same program of reducing labor, said Equamo
without confirming whether the contracts of expatriate workers
will be renewed or not.
</P>
<P>
There are Zambians on contract as well as expatriates. So
when their contracts expire, the management will come in to
determine whether they will need their services or not, according
to Equamo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
