<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tides Cost About Nine Million US Dollars Losses in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- About two-thirds of 1,500 fish
farmers in Hong Kong have been affected by red tides which
resulted in a direct estimated economic losses of 70 million HK
dollars (8.97 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers reported here Sunday that the red tides first
emerged in mid-March and then spread widely on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The papers quoted Wong Yung-kan, chairman of the Hong Kong Fish
Culture Association, as saying "unlike previous tides, which were
over in three or four days, this year it has fast spread out."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Agriculture and Fisheries Department
has provided farm owners with emergency aid subsidies since the
red tides occurred.
</P>
<P>
According to a local expert, the red tides, known as
micro-organisms, bred tremendously fast when the water temperature
rose to a certain level.
</P>
<P>
They breed so fast that their number can double in an hour.
During the breeding process, they acquire a tremendous volume of
oxygen and release toxic substances which suffocate fish in the
farms, the expert added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
