<HEADLINE> Deaf-Mute People Create Job Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A deaf-mute worker in Fushun
city, in northeast China's Liaoning Province, started his own
business after being laid-off, and then employed a dozen other
laid-off workers, eight of whom are disabled persons.
</P>
<P>
Lu Zhenshan, 56, was laid off 14 years ago by a chemical
factory, as was his deaf-mute wife.
</P>
<P>
In the years that followed he made a living by repairing motor
vehicles, until he had saved up enough to start his own business.
</P>
<P>
In August 1996, with the assistance of the local government, he
set up his own company dealing in telecommunication facilities.
</P>
<P>
Unable to speak or hear, Lu relies on quality products, a good
reputation and talented staff for his success.
</P>
<P>
Besides the facts that he pays taxes to the state and
re-employs laid-off workers, Lu's usefulness as a citizen extends
to never hesitating to help other disabled people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
