<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga Sunday called for peace in her ethnic conflict-torn
country and said the celebration of the New Year was a "strong
unifying thread in the fabric of relationship between the
Sinhalese and Tamil people."
</P>
<P>
The majority Sinhalese community and the minority Tamils in Sri
Lanka celebrate their common New Year on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In her message to the nation on the New Year, Kumaratunga said:
"the message of the new year is that we must end the war by
unifying our fractured land. This is what our brave combatants are
fighting for."
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has long been plagued by problems between the
Sinhalese and Tamil-- the two major ethnic groups in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) has been fighting a
war against the government for a separate Tamil state in the north
and east of the country since 1983. The government says at least
50,000 people have been killed in the war.
</P>
<P>
"We must go forward on the path of peace," the president said
in her message.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective is to create a society in which members of all
communities can live with honor and security while retaining their
unique identities," she said.  
