<HEADLINE> Philippine President Returns From U.S. Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
returned here Sunday from a four-day official visit to the United
States, which he described as "fruitful."
</P>
<P>
In his arrival statement, Ramos said his visit had brought to
the American people and the world a message "about what we
Filipinos are proud of, and what we as a nation stand for."
</P>
<P>
In his discussions with President Bill Clinton and other U.S.
officials, Ramos said, he stressed that the Philippine government
will play a proactive role in ensuring peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"This role means the Philippines' active involvement in efforts
to find peaceful solutions to the situation in Cambodia, the
Korean peninsula and elsewhere," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, which currently holds the chairmanship of the
Standing Committee of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN), the ASEAN Region Forum and the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting,
has a special responsibility to advance cooperation and build
confidence among the countries in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Ramos also met officials of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank, as well as U.S.
businessmen to seek more financial assistance and foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the Philippine economy has fared well and is posed
to return to sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' exit from the IMF supervision -- under 22 IMF
programs over the last 35 years -- last month is "a clear signal
of the economy's new-found strength," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, in his meeting with Clinton, Ramos failed to find
immediate solutions to two key issues -- the return of two
Philippine church bells seized by the American forces at the end
of the Philippine-American War in 1904, and the increase of
benefits for the Filipino veterans who fought with American troops
in World War II.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said efforts will continue to secure the return of at
least one of the two bells.
</P>
<P>
He added that Clinton also assured him of his "strong personal
effort" to have one of the bells returned to the Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
