<HEADLINE> Vietnam Announces Major Lay-offs in State-owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Ministry of Labor, War
Invalids and Social Affairs has announced major lay-offs at both
state-owned and foreign-invested companies due to the regional
monetary crisis, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
8 percent of the work force at state-owned companies and 11
percent of the employees at foreign-invested companies have been
cut, said VNA.
</P>
<P>
Industry, agriculture and construction -- the three biggest
economic sectors -- had laid-off 16 percent, 12 percent and eight
percent of their workers respectively.
</P>
<P>
A sharp drop in the cost of labor in financially stricken
countries like South Korea and Thailand has made many foreign
companies reduce or postpone their orders with Vietnamese firms
and reduce investment.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted at 1,855 businesses found substantial drops
in export orders in sectors such as garment and footwear, and
showed 747 of the firms cannot find enough work for their
employees.
</P>
<P>
Labor experts say the number of the jobless people may swell to
as many as 80,000 nationwide. Some 53,000 people have been jobless
for years, Vietnam Courier Weekly quoted sources from the ministry
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some companies have tried to avoid lay-offs by reducing working
hours, shifting them to other jobs, granting extended vacations
and reducing foreign staff.
</P>
<P>
But experts fear the shut-down of the state-owned enterprises
with protracted losses are likely to make unemployment worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Might Pull out From INRO: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia might pull out of
the International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) if Thailand
does so, its Primary Industries Minister said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lim Keng Yaik said Malaysia is considering doing so because
both countries share the sentiment that the rubber consumer
countries are being very unfair towards the producer countries,
the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the question arose after a recent INRO meeting at which
Thailand expressed dissatisfaction with the consistent drop of
world natural rubber prices in the light of the regional economic
downturn.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia had actually wanted to withdraw its membership from
the organization two years ago but delayed doing so in the "spirit
of ASEAN," he told reporters after chairing a party meeting in
Johor Baharu, southern Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is the world's third largest rubber producing country
after Thailand and Indonesia. It produces one million tons of
natural rubber annually, about 800,000 of which is exported to
consumer countries. But Malaysia also imports some 400,000 tons
annually from its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The INRO, set up in 1978, brings together six rubber producer
countries, which are third world countries, and 21 rubber consumer
countries including those from Europe, and the United States and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
It serves to stabilize rubber prices by regulating the demand
and supply of rubber in the international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
