<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's LTTE Seeks Talks With Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) has told the Jaffna city Catholic Bishop B.T.
Saundaranayagam it is ready to negotiate a solution to the ethnic
conflict through a third party mediation but the Sri Lankan
government must take the initiative, a Tamil newspaper from north
of the country reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A Jaffna-based Tamil Daily Udayan said the Bishop met several
LTTE leaders for extensive discussions on humanitarian, social and
political issues when he visited the rebel-controlled areas in the
northern Wanni district recently.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE leaders who refused to accept the Sri Lankan
government's devolution package as a basis for talks, pointed out
that even the two main political parties -- the People's Alliance
and the United National Party were at odds on the package, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The devolution package announced by the government in August,
1995, aims to resolve the long-standing ethnic crisis in the
country. It contains proposals for redemarcation of the north and
east provinces and extension of more powers to Tamils in these
provinces.
</P>
<P>
However the Sri Lankan government announced to ban the LTTE on
January 26 this year. The decision came one day after a powerful
truck bomb exploded in Kandy, the ancient Sri Lankan capital 115
km of Colombo, killing 12 people and damaging the holiest place of
worship of Sri Lankan Buddhists, the Tooth relic Temple.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting for a war against the government for
a separate Tamil state in the north and east of the country since
1983. the government said at least 50,000 people have been killed
in the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
