<HEADLINE> Ramos Approves Additional Food Aid to Drought Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Sunday approved the release of additional 13 million pesos (about
320,000 U.S. dollars) as food aid for 105,000 families in
Mindanao, where the death toll from the El Nino-induced drought
has climbed to 36.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here, the presidential office said that
last week the government released 10 million pesos (250,000
dollars) for food assistance to the families affected by the
drought.
</P>
<P>
Of the 13 million pesos of new aid, 11.4 million pesos will be
used to pay for the rice being distributed by the National Food
Authority, 600,000 pesos for the relief operation expense, and 1
million pesos for a malnutrition program for the region, the
office said.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health said earlier that acute and chronic
malnutrition is prevalent among children in the Mindanao region
and of the 36 deaths reported as of last Thursday, 10 died of
poisoning from eating wild yams.
</P>
<P>
The presidential office said that the Department of Health has
already sent medical teams with the necessary medications to treat
the victims and conducted public information campaigns to prevent
food poisoning. 
</P>
