<HEADLINE> Progress Made in Somalia's Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- progress has been made in
Somalia's reconciliation and reconstruction efforts, the local
newspaper Sunday Nation quoted Somali faction leader Hussein
Aideed as reporting.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the newspaper Saturday, the 36-year old
Somali faction leader said that the Somali people were tired of
fighting and the number of people crusading for peace and
national reconciliation was increasing day by day.
</P>
<P>
"Things have changed, we are no longer shooting each other.
These days we (factional leaders) sit and dine together," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Aideed said, "When I was coming to Kenya, I shared a flight
with Ali Mahdi Mohammed, Osman Hassan Ali and Mohammed Afrah.
That is how close we have become."
</P>
<P>
He called on African states to support his country in the
struggle to reclaim its lost glory and reverse the havoc caused
by seven years of civil strife.
</P>
<P>
The Somali faction leader blamed the disintegration of the
horn-of-Africa country on interference from the West and former
Somali leader Siad Barre's divide-and-rule tactics during his 21
years of tyrannical rule.
</P>
<P>
He is among the four faction leaders from Somalia's Banadir
region who arrived here last Tuesday and met Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Like his father (the late Farrah Aideed), Aideed said, he is
prepared to die if this is the inevitable price to pay to end the
disintegration of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"If we did not have faith in the reconciliation efforts by
Kenya and our other friends, we would not be wasting time
attending peace meetings," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference last Wednesday, Aideed said,"We
are determined more than ever before to pursue the path of peace
in order to resolve our political and other differences."
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that they were in the process of establishing a
central authority within the Banadir region including Mogadishu
and its environs, and they had invited President Moi to perform
the official reopening of seaport and airport in Mogadishu.
</P>
</TEXT>
