<HEADLINE> China-Made Game Software Gaining More Lights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- ``Iron Armor Storm'', software
for a computer game developed in China, made its debut here
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At a launching ceremony, officials from China's Press and
Publications Administration (PPA) said that the software,
developed by Object Software Co. (OSC), has caught up with the
international level in terms of programming and designing.
</P>
<P>
The development of the software costs two million yuan, a
considerable amount for a domestic software program. An English
version of the program will be issued overseas in a month.
</P>
<P>
The company hopes to sell 10,000 items of the software in the
Taiwan and Southeast Asian markets, and 30,000-40,000 in the
European and American regions, according to OSC's chief designer,
who is also the executive manager of the company, one of the
leading specialized game software developers in China.
</P>
<P>
The development growth of China's copyrighted game softwares
has been fairly slow, said the PPA officials, due to a flood of
imported programs and software, lack of domestic financing and
copyright piracy.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China developed 1,250 varieties
of software in 1997, only six percent of which were game CDs. At
the same time, imported game products totaled 110 varieties.
</P>
<P>
The PPA is reportedly working on issuing publishing licenses
for electronic publication to some enterprises. This right has been
reserved for publishing houses so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
