<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fires Destroy 21,000 Hectares of Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- About 21,000 hectares of forest
land, plantation and graze lands in the Philippines have been
destroyed by fires since January this year, exceeding the
country's 15,000 hectare annual average rate of forest fire
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The trend shows an escalating incidence of forest fires since
the start of 1998 compared to the decreased incidence of forest
fires in 1996 and 1997, the Star newspaper said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the Philippines will still have to brace
for more forest fires as El Nino is expected to stay for more than
a month longer.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the 1997-98 El Nino will continue up to May
or early June, thus delaying the onset of the rainy season in the
country for weeks.
</P>
<P>
Annually, the paper said, forest fires cost the government
close to 80 million pesos (about 2 million U.S. dollars) worth of
plantations and reforestation areas.
</P>
<P>
This, according to the Department of Environment and Natural
Resources, represents 12.49 percent of the national deforestation
rate of 118,000 hectares annually.
</P>
<P>
Eight provinces in the Philippines have been hit by forest
fires since January. On the island of Palawan, fires have damaged
15,000 hectares of forest in a month. New fires have been reported
across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Imposing Fishing Ban In Adjacent Maritime Areas This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (xinhua) -- China will impose a new fishing
ban in the Yellow and East China seas this year to protect fish
resources, the Agriculture Ministry's Fishery Bureau announced
today.
</P>
<P>
The ban was approved by the State Council and is similar to the
one imposed in the summer of 1995. The practice was then repeated
for the following two years and has had good results. Statistics
show a hairtail output increase of 15.5 percent and yellow croaker
increase of 37.8 percent for the autumn high water season of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new fishing ban increases the length of the no-fishing
season from two months to three months.
</P>
<P>
It will exclude trawlers and net catches by sailboats, from
midnight of June 15 to midnight of September 15, from an area
extending from 26 degrees to 35 degrees north latitude, and from
midnight of June 30 to midnight of August 31, in an area north to
35 degrees of north latitude.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Earnings From Leather Export Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's earnings from leather
export has declined over the last few years due to lack of proper
policy support, shortage of sufficient capital, and smuggling of
raw hides and skin out of the country during the Eid-ul-Azha
festival period.
</P>
<P>
The Export Promotion Bureau has set a target of 205 million
U.S. dollars for leather export during the 1997-98 fiscal year,
but only 89.10 million dollars were earned in the first half of
the year from July to December, which was over 13 percent lower
than the target for that period, press reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The country's tanning industry, which requires about 180
million square feet of raw hides and skin, usually collects about
72 million square feet each year (more than 40 percent of the
total requirement) during Eid, according to the Bangladesh
Tanneries Association.
</P>
<P>
But most local tannery owners could not collect enough hides
and skin of the sacrificial cattle this year during the festival
of Eid-ul-Azha which falls on April 8, due to fund constraint. And
about 50 percent of the tannery owners could not purchase hides
and skin because of lack of fund, although the prices of hides and
skin were very low, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Bank, the nation's central bank, has advised the
commercial banks not to give fresh loan before Eid to defaulters.
Since 1990, commercial banks have provided over 12 billion taka
(about 260.9 million dollars) to the leather sector, of which 7.72
billion taka (about 167.8 million dollars), or more than 63
percent of the total credit, have now become bad loan.
</P>
<P>
As the local buyers failed to collect the raw hides and skin, a
huge quantity of raw hides and skin remained unsold till the Eid
night on April 8, and was likely to be smuggled to India,
according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The country has banned export of raw hides and skin of animals
since 1990 to protect the interests of local tanneries and leather
goods producers.
</P>
<P>
The target set for this year was lower that the targeted 260
million dollars for the 1996-97 fiscal year, when actual export
earnings amounted to 166 million dollars only. The country earned
202 million dollars from leather export in the 1994-95 fiscal
year, and 235 million dollars in the 1995-96 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Leather export is a major foreign exchange earner of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
