Bangladesh Bank, the nation's central bank, has advised the
commercial banks not to give fresh loan before Eid to defaulters.
Since 1990, commercial banks have provided over 12 billion taka
(about 260.9 million dollars) to the leather sector, of which 7.72
billion taka (about 167.8 million dollars), or more than 63
percent of the total credit, have now become bad loan.
</P>
<P>
As the local buyers failed to collect the raw hides and skin, a
huge quantity of raw hides and skin remained unsold till the Eid
night on April 8, and was likely to be smuggled to India,
according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The country has banned export of raw hides and skin of animals
since 1990 to protect the interests of local tanneries and leather
goods producers.
</P>
<P>
The target set for this year was lower that the targeted 260
million dollars for the 1996-97 fiscal year, when actual export
earnings amounted to 166 million dollars only. The country earned
202 million dollars from leather export in the 1994-95 fiscal
year, and 235 million dollars in the 1995-96 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Leather export is a major foreign exchange earner of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980412.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesian Govt Dealing With Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- In the face of food shortage
threat, the Indonesian government is taking steps to introduce a
better technology system to accelerate production of basic food
crops, particularly staple rice, soybean and corn.
</P>
<P>
According to Agriculture Minister Justike S. Baharsyah, the
technology system, named Sistem Usaha Pertanian (SUP), is aimed to
enable the use of less arable land for growing crops. It includes
the use of high-yielding and insect-resisting seeds that can be
planted in swamp area.
</P>
<P>
"By applying SUP we can, for example, produce five to eight
tons of unhusked rice for one hectare of rice field in swamp
area," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Government officials and agriculture experts have suggested
that use of swamps for rice fields has become increasingly
important in the face shrinking arable land in Java, the most
populous island in the country, where 30,000 to 40,000 hectares of
agricultural land are turned into industrial or residential zones
each year.
</P>
<P>
So far, Indonesia has applied the SUP system to corn on West
Nusa Tenggara province and worked well, officials said.
</P>
<P>
But, Baharsyah held that the use of better technology alone is
not enough to boost production. To encourage farmers to produce
more, there has to be a partnership between farmers and business
people, who can help the funding and further process the farmers'
agricultural products, she added.
</P>
<P>
In the corn cultivation area in West Nusa Tenggara province,
the ministers said there are companies that are specialized in
providing corn seeds, a bank that offers credit line and a company
that is ready buy the farmers' output.
</P>
<P>
"Under such a cooperation framework, farmers will have the
resources to plant and know that there will be a company to buy
their output," said Picko Nyotosetiadi, director of PT. Citra
Gemini Mulya, a company that buys and markets the output.
</P>
<P>
The Agricultural Ministry has also cultivated 30,000 hectares
of swamp area rice field in South Sumatra province. It plans to
expand the use of swamp area in the province to 270,000 hectares
over the next five years, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The government's effort to boost basic food production has come
amid warnings from international agencies that the country may
face a record food deficit as a result of reduced harvests. In the
meantime, Indonesia's ability to buy food from overseas has been
reduced because of the current monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
A mission sent by the UN Food and Agricultural Organization
(FAO) and the World Food Program (WFP) recently estimated that
approximately 7.5 million poor Indonesians in 15 provinces may
face acute food shortages during the coming dry season (from April
to September).
</P>
<P>
Because of the steep production fall, Indonesia is expected to
face a record import requirement of about 3.5 million tons of rice
during the 1998-99 fiscal year (starting April 1), economic
analysts predicted.
</P>
<P>
Although Indonesia is rich in natural resources, it needs to
import at least 1.2 million tons of sugar, 1.3 million tons of
corn and 1 million tons of soybean each year. The country imported
1 million tons of rice last year.
</P>
<P>
Besides these commodities, Indonesia, with a population of
202.5 million, also imports meat, milk and milk products, fruits
and other goods to meet its demand.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia achieved rice self-sufficiency for the first time in
1984, but unfortunately it did not last long due to a prolonged
dry spell. Since early 1990s, the country has again become a net
rice importer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
