<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke041210 -News Analysis: How Successful Ramos' Washington Trip? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
returned home Sunday after a four-day official visit to the United
States, which the president described as "very successful."
</P>
<P>
Ramos' trip to Washington, which was made less than three
months before his six-year term ends, was criticized by opposition
parties for "wasting money" when the country is passing through a
regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, the administration said the visit is necessary since
the country is badly in need of foreign investments to stimulate
the economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
In that sense, analysts said, Ramos' visit is "successful" as
it has helped boost investors' confidence in the Philippine
economy.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Ramos had met World Bank President James
Wolfensohn, International Monetary Fund (IMF) Managing Director
Michel Camdessus, and U.S. businessmen, including W. Wayne Booker,
vice chairman of Ford Motor Company.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to dissipate fears of dis-continuation of reforms
after the May 11 presidential election in the Philippines, Ramos
assured them that the Philippines' economic policies would not be
reversed, regardless of who wins the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In response to the assurance, the IMF, World bank officials and
U.S. businessmen had pledged their assistance to the Philippines,
which is recovering from the nine-month old financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, the World Bank and the Philippines signed an
agreement on the bank's 79 million dollars special loan to the
Southeast Asian country. Ramos and Wolfensohn attended the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The money, part of the 1-billion-dollar aid package by the
world bank to the Philippines, will be used for three projects
aimed to increase the income of the poor and provide basic
services, especially those in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Although the Philippines exited from the IMF supervision of its
economy on March 27, the monetary body agreed to provide the
country with a stand-by credit of 1.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
For the part of Ford Motor Company, it also announced during
Ramos' trip that it will put up a 330-million-dollar integrated
car manufacturing plant in the Philippines, a strong signal of
confidence that U.S. manufacturers have in the country.
</P>
<P>
But compared with Ramos' campaign for foreign investments, his
visit seems not as successful as the Philippine leader had
expected, observers said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Ramos and U.S. President held brief talks with
agreement to strengthen economic ties, but failed to solve
disputes over the return of two Philippine church bells and the
benefits that Filipino veterans who had fought with the American
forces in the World War ii want to get.
</P>
<P>
The two church bells were originally installed in the village of
Balangiga on the island of Samar, the Philippines. They were used
to signal the villagers.
</P>
<P>
They were taken by the U.S. 11th Infantry in 1901 when the U.S.
troops captured the village and burned Balangiga to the ground and
killed every male over the age of 10 in retaliation on behalf of
the 9th Infantry. Later, the 11th Infantry took the two church
bells to Wyoming in 1904 when the troops were sent back to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that Ramos' failure to resolve the
issues of the church bells and veterans' benefits has made his
trip less successful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
