<HEADLINE> Mount Qomolangma Glaciers Shrinking: Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have found that
glaciers in the Mount Qomolangma area have been shrinking over the
past three decades or so.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Lanzhou Glacier and Tundra Research Institute
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences said that, compared with
1966 statistics, the largest glacier in the area has shrunk from
170 m and 270 m thick over the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese scientists made investigation of glaciers in the
area from late 1950s to 1970s. latest research work was carried
out in May last year by the institute in cooperation with the New
Hampshire University of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that scientific research over the past three
decades has shown that among 19 registered glaciers in the area,
nearly half are shrinking.
</P>
<P>
They tentatively blame this phenomenon on global warming.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
