<HEADLINE> Peru Reduces Coca Acreage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian government has decided
to cut 28 percent of the country's coca growing area this year, in
a bid to eliminate drug production, a Peruvian official said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The cut will bring down Peru's acreage of coca shrubs from the
present 69,000 hectares to 50,000 hectares by the end of 1998,
said Juan Gil, executive secretary of the Commission for the War
Against Drug Consuming.
</P>
<P>
The cultivation of coca, whose dried leaves can be used to
produce cocaine, could be finally wiped out in the country, Gil
said.
</P>
<P>
"Our country will have completely substituted in less than 10
years this kind of cultivation with other crops, such as rice,
coffee, cocoa, and palmetto, as a result of the implementation of
the National Program for Alternate Development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gil noted that with proper registration, only a small area of
coca shrubs will be kept to meet the needs of the medicine and the
traditional use by the Andean population.
</P>
<P>
However, Gil said that the substitution plan must go together
with social programs that can give farmers necessary mechanism to
market their new produce.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this goal, the Peruvian government has decided to
pump money into state institutions in coca-producing areas to help
farmers adapt themselves to the change. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
