<HEADLINE> Stronger Baht Cuts Thai Export Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's export value in March
dropped to 198 billion baht (5.2 billion U.S. dollars) as the baht
grew stronger against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The export value for February and January was 220 billion baht
(5.8 billion dollars) and 219 billion baht (5.7 billion dollars)
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's trade surplus, however, surged to 138 billion baht
(3.6 billion dollars) in the first quarter of this year, Customs
Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
This was the third month that Thailand registered a trade
surplus.
</P>
<P>
Import value for the first quarter of this year fell to 156.9
billion baht (4.1 billion dollars) against 169 billion baht (4.4
billion dollars) in February and 173.69 billion baht (4.6 billion
dollars) in January. Sunday's Nation newspaper quoted the
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 exports of February continued into March. They
included computers and parts, electric appliances, garments,
rubber and rubber products, rice, canned sea food and gems.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 imports included electrical machinery, chemicals,
integrated circuits, crude oil, steel, and basic metal products.
</P>
<P>
The most important export market was the United States, with
42.22 billion baht (1.1 billion dollars) in export value, to be
followed by the ASEAN market, with export value reaching 36.92
billion baht (971 million dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
