<HEADLINE> Thailand's Central Bank to Ease Credit Squeeze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Central Bank is
considering steps to improve conditions by restructuring the debts
of state banks and easing loan classification rules for financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank is showing signs of flexibility amid growing
concern about lack of liquidity in the monetary market, according
to its officials.
</P>
<P>
But any reclassification of non-performing loans will be done
on a case-by-case basis, the officials said in remarks published
by major newspapers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Relaxing the classification rules would reduce pressure on
financial institutions to set aside provisions and thus free up
funds for credit expansion.
</P>
<P>
Businesses have been finding it almost impossible to obtain
loans as banks are concerned about possible bad debts and the need
to set aside ever-growing sums as provisions.
</P>
<P>
The officials said bank regulators would meet with the Thai
Bankers' Association next week to discuss ways to ease competition
for deposits amid mounting efforts by many banks to offer high
deposit interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank was also studying how to restructure the
funding structure of the financial institutions development fund.
</P>
<P>
The government has said it would issue long-term bonds to
reduce funding costs of the fund, which in turn would create room
for interest rates to ease.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank is expected to gradually ease interest rates
through the bond repurchase market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
