<HEADLINE> Northeast China City to Use More Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang, an old heavy
industrial base and capital of northeast China's Liaoning
province, plans to seek more overseas funds to revitalize its
state businesses in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Xu Wencai, secretary of the city committee of the Communist
Party of China (CPC), said over 37 percent of the city's 224 large
and medium-sized state enterprises had used overseas investment by
the end of last year, which he said, "was not enough to turn
around those Shenyang state businesses operating in the red,"
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Known as the "cradle of Chinese modern industry" in the 1950s
and 1960s, the city now boasts over 5,500 state-run businesses,
many of which have been operating in the red since China introduced
the market competition to its industries beginning the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that factors attributing to the poor performance
of those businesses are two-fold: out-of-date management and
unpopular products.  
</P>
