<HEADLINE> Mexico May Need to Import 14 Million Tons of Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Mexico will need to import
some 14 million tons of grain in the wake of a poor production of
corn, beans, wheat and sorghum this year, a senior farmhand union
official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Mexican newspaper, Uno Mas Uno,
Alvaro Lopez Ramos, general secretary of the National Agricultural
Workers Union (UNTA), attributed this year's deficit in the grain
production to the drought caused by the climate phenomenon El Nino.
</P>
<P>
The UNTA leader added that the country's central and northern
regions suffered the most in the drought.
</P>
<P>
The National Water Commission revealed that the water in the
country's 137 main reservoirs available for irrigation is 15,713
million cubic meters, representing merely 33 percent of their
capacity.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from other similar farm labor unions echoed the UNTA
leader's opinion, complaining that the government's agricultural
policies are insufficient and ineffective.
</P>
<P>
They demanded more resources for the agricultural sector and
revision of policies for rural development. 
</P>
