<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke041201 -News Analysis: Asian Airlines Feel Bites of Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Asian airlines that expanded
rapidly during recent years have begun to feel the pinch of the
protracted financial crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
In a surprisingly frank admission of its ailing financial
health, Philippine Airlines (PAL) likened itself in a recent
communique to a "sick man" facing an "uncertain future."
</P>
<P>
"Due to the recent currency crisis in the region, Philippine
Airlines is in serious financial trouble and will not survive
unless we take drastic steps," PAL president Jose Antonio Garcia
said in the communique issued to its 14,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
Garcia said the airline must shrink its operations by reducing
its fleet, cutting its workforce, closing stations and reducing
flight frequencies.
</P>
<P>
Last month, PAL announced it would indefinitely postpone orders
for nine aircraft, part of its 4-billion-U.S.-dollar modernization
program starting in 1996. These include six Boeing 747-400s, which
were scheduled to be delivered in the next three years, and three
Airbuses.
</P>
<P>
PAL's financial difficulty was merely the tip of the iceberg.
Many other major airlines in the region have already suffered the
fall-out effects of the Asia's financial woes.
</P>
<P>
Garuda Indonesia has reportedly defaulted two installment on
loans for two Airbus airplanes.
</P>
<P>
Two other Southeast Asian carriers -- Thai Airways
International and South Korea's Asiana -- are asking for delays of
planes to be delivered this year.
</P>
<P>
Some airlines have already begun to make arrangements for
selling and leasing back part of their fleet as a means to raise
money and to stay in the air.
</P>
<P>
Asian airlines, having returned to profitability during the
past several years, have been predicted better days ahead as
passenger volumes were expected to surge over the coming years as
a result of booming economies.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the currency crisis roiling the region since last
July, most of the major Asian carriers were poised for a big
takeoff to compete with the world's leading carriers.
</P>
<P>
Many Asian airlines have gone into multi-billion-dollar
modernization programs in anticipation of a continued economic
boom in the region, which has been seen as a big market by both
Boeing Co. and Airbus Industries.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines launched in 1996 a 4-billion-dollar
modernization plan under which 3.2 billion dollars will be
allocated to purchase 36 new planes. The PAL's new fleet would
have been one of the youngest in the region.
</P>
<P>
One year later, Korean Airlines (KAL) approved plans to
introduce at least 140 new aircraft to its fleet by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many new airline companies were born in the region,
including Korea's Asiana Airline and a second national carrier for
Thailand, the Angel Airlines.
</P>
<P>
But the downside came soon after the floatation of the Thai
baht last July which ignited the Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Because of a sharp drop in the Asian currencies against the
U.S. dollar, Asian airlines' costs surged since many of their
expenses, such as fuel and aircraft purchase, are paid in dollars.
And half of their revenues are in local currencies.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the currency crisis has dealt a severe blow to the
regional tourism industry whose growth mainly depends on tourists
within the region.
</P>
<P>
Because of the region's financial turmoil, Asia-Pacific nations
lost 12 million tourists in 1997 -- a loss likely to be repeated
in each of the next two years, according to a recent report from
the World Tourism Organization.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the revenues of the airlines have shrunk as
passenger volumes were drastically reduced.
</P>
<P>
More airlines, especially small domestic ones, may have to
cancel orders, defer deliveries or sell older planes as the
financial crisis continued to persist in the region, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
Due to economic slowdown in the region, it will take a long
time for Asian airlines to recover. And for most cash-strapped
airlines, just to survive this year will be a big achievement,
they predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
