<HEADLINE> Coulthard Takes Pole Position in Argentina Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Scot driver David Coulthard
claimed his first pole position in three years when he put his
McLaren Mercedes in top spot during Saturday's qualifying for the
Argentina Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Coulthard clocked one minute 25.852 seconds round the slippery,
bumpy 2.646 mile circuit.
</P>
<P>
But instead of his teammate Mika Hakkinen, who has won the
opening two races of the season, lining up beside him on the front
row, he will make the dash to the first bend with the Ferrari of
Michael Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
The double world champion, revelling in the tricky conditions,
clocked 1:26.251.
</P>
<P>
Hakkinen could only manage third fastest, just ahead of the
other Ferrari of Eddie Irvine.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Jacques Villeneuve had to settle for the
fourth row. But his Williams teammate Heinz-Harald Frentzen, who
has consistently outraced him this season, was sixth fastest and
will line-up aside Ralf Schumacher in the Jordan.
</P>
<P>
A disappointed Damon Hill in the second Jordan was ninth
fastest. It was a bitter blow for the former champion who was
fifth fastest in the morning's unofficial practice session.
